<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Schoenoplectus</i> <i>americanus</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the herbaceous layer with <i>Anemopsis</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Argentina</i> <i>egedii</i>, <i>Distichlis</i> <i>spicata</i>, <i>Juncus</i> <i>arcticus</i>, <i>Juncus</i> <i>cooperi</i>, <i>Phragmites</i> <i>australis</i>, <i>Schoenoplectus</i> <i>acutus</i>, <i>Schoenoplectus</i> <i>californicus</i>, <i>Schoenoplectus</i> <i>pungens</i> and <i>Typha</i> spp. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 4 m; cover is intermittent to continuous. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Schoenoplectus americanus</i> > 50% relative cover in the herbaceous layer (Keeler-Wolf and Vaghti 2000).</li>
		
		<li><i>Schoenoplectus americanus</i> ≥ 10% absolute cover in the herbaceous layer; relatively dominant in submerged or sparse stands (S. Smith 1998).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Along streams; around ponds and lakes; and in sloughs, swamps, fresh and brackish marshes, and roadside ditches. Soils have a high organic content and are poorly aerated. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Schoenoplectus americanus</i> as an OBL plant. </div>
</div>

        
