<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Schoenoplectus americanus </i>is a moderately tall tule that attains 2 m in height. The triangular aerial culms are winter deciduous, arising from long, stout, underground rhizomes. Plants produce dark-brown achenes that are dispersed by water and birds. Seeds undergo a period of ripening, requiring 18 months or more before germination can occur. They remain dormant as long as they are submerged in water, forming a seed bank. Germination and seedling establishment occur when mudflats are not flooded. Germination decreases with increasing salinity (USDA-NRCS 2005, Uchytil 1992b). Other names used in the older botanical literature are <i>Scirpus americanus </i>and <i>S. olneyi</i>. <br/>
<br/>
The <i>Schoenoplectus americanus </i>alliance occurs in many wetlands throughout the western United States and the southern Great Plains (NatureServe 2007a). Stands have a high organic-matter accumulation from extensive root/rhizome systems (Shupe et al. 1986, Ungar 1965). Most stands in California are associated with inland wetlands adjacent to alkali playas and seeps, but they also occur in coastal brackish marshes (Grewell et al. 2007). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
