    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa-d). Stands occur in the mid-marsh zone, especially in wet years, and in freshwater marshes at the San Francisco Bay estuary; they are either pure or mixed with other tules and cattails (Baye et al. 2000, Holstein 2000).</li>
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Ca-c). Stands occur in marshes in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park and elsewhere in the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ai-l, Ar, Av, Ay). Stands in the Sacramento-San Joaquin River delta occupy the protected inner portions of brackish marshes away from open bays and large sloughs, commonly occurring with stands of <i>Distichlis spicata</i> and <i>Typha</i> (<i>angustifolia, domingensis, latifolia</i>) alliances (Hickson and Keeler-Wolf 2007). Stands in Suisun Marsh occur in managed marshes (Baye et al. 2000, Keeler-Wolf and Vaghti 2000), which provide habitat for rare CNPS list 1B species, <i>Cirsium hydrophilum</i> var. <i>hydrophilum</i> and <i>Symphyotrichum lentum,</i> and for the invasive <i>Lepidium latifolium.</i> Stands of the more flood-tolerant <i>S. americanus</i> expand in wet years (Grewell et al. 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Ge, Gg). Stands are rare in the lower-elevation inland portions of the section (S. Smith 1998b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa-i, Ak, Am-p). Stands occur in a mosaic with various alliances that segregate based on moisture and alkalinity/salinity tolerances. Stands of <i>Schoenoplectus americanus</i> occur in the wettest settings along with stands of <i>Distichlis spicata, Juncus cooperi, Phragmites australis, Pluchea sericea, Sporobolus airoides,</i> and <i>Typha</i> alliances. Largest stands in the section may be along the Amargosa River between Shoshone and Tecopa (Thomas et al. 2004). Others exist in Death Valley National Park (Bradley 1970) and near Zzyzx.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341De, Di). Stands occur at Fish Slough in the Owens Valley (Odion et al. 1992a).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa, Ac). Unmapped stands occur at Lake Earl Wildlife Area-Lake Tolowa State Park in a brackish lagoon system with <i>Argentina egedii, Carex obnupta,</i> and <i>Juncus</i> spp. (Eicher and Geldin-Meyers 1988, Hehnke 1969). Stands also occur along San Pablo Bay near the Carquinez Straights.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba, Bd-e). Stands occur along the Lower Colorado River.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> The alliance is a widespread marsh type in the state, and it provides habitat for wildlife. Seeds and stems of <i>Schoenoplectus americanus </i>and related species are very important food and cover. Most stands have been altered to supply water for irrigation. Maintenance of stands depends primarily on water levels and salinity levels. Grazing and invasive non-native plants (e.g., <i>Lepidium latifolium, Tamarix </i>spp.) are other problems. 

Its extent is much smaller today because of alteration for agricultural use. Vaghti and Greco (2007) estimated that stands in the Sacramento-San Joaquin River delta of this and related alliances covered approximately 1.2 million ha prior to the mid 1800s. Stands dominated by tules for thousands of years are responsible for producing the deep layers of peat. Cultivation, de-watering, subsequent aeration of these previously anaerobic substrates, and fires have resulted in widespread slumping of the delta islands to as much as 10 m below sea level, which contributes to the delta’s significant levee management issues. Fires of fossil peat adjacent to desert playas have occurred at Koehn Dry Lake (M. Faul, pers. comm. 2000). </div>
</div>

    

    

